# Filament table toolbar standards

Every **data table** (list resources, relation managers, custom pages, table widgets) must expose:

| Control | Requirement |
|---------|-------------|
| **Show / hide columns** | Enabled globally via `Table::configureUsing()` → `columnManager()` in `AppServiceProvider`. Do not disable unless the grid is a fixed-layout special case (document why). |
| **Filters** | At least one `->filters([...])` entry (status, date range, ternary, or domain filter). Use `DateColumnRangeFilter` for dates. |
| **Group by** | Chain `TableGrouping::apply($table, TableGrouping::…())` with domain-appropriate groups (collapsible). |
| **Bulk actions** | `->toolbarActions()` with at least one `BulkActionGroup`. Mutating row actions need matching bulk counterparts. Read-only grids use `TableStandards::defaultToolbarActions()` or `TableToolbar::refreshBulkAction()`. |

## Row actions

- Use `TableRecordActionGroups::apply($table, $actions, recordUrl: …)` when configuring record actions.
- When the list contains **only** a `ViewAction` or `EditAction`, the row opens that action on click and **no actions column** is rendered (pass `recordUrl` for page navigation, omit for modal view actions). `TableGrouping::apply()` enforces this automatically for tables that use `->recordActions(TableRecordActionGroups::wrap([…]))`.
- When multiple row actions exist, use `TableRecordActionGroups::wrap([...])` via `apply()` or chain `->recordActions(TableRecordActionGroups::wrap([...]))`.
- Do not leave bare `Action` / `EditAction` / `ViewAction` at the top level of `recordActions()` unless wrapped by `apply()` / `wrap()`.

## Helpers

- `App\Filament\Support\TableGrouping` — group-by definitions per domain
- `App\Filament\Support\TableToolbar` — refresh bulk action, `bulkGroup()`
- `App\Filament\Support\TableRecordActionGroups` — `apply()` for view-only row click; `wrap()` for action groups
- `App\Filament\Support\TableStandards` — `defaultToolbarActions()` for read-only tables

## Account transaction ledgers

Tenant account transaction relation managers use `headerActions()` for Credit / Debit / Refund via `AccountTransactionManualAdjustmentHeaderActions`. Member-facing ledgers do not expose manual adjustments.

## Tests

`tests/Architecture/FilamentTableStandardsTest.php` guards tables that define columns but omit filters, grouping, or bulk toolbar actions.
